# Known Test Failures

Failures listed here are **pre-existing — NOT regressions**. During
Stage 3 — Review, `qa-engineer` compares any failing test against this table:
listed and unchanged → note it and move on; not listed → it is new, and it
blocks (`QA REJECTED ❌` with a `[TEST FAILURE]` finding).

| Test | First seen | Last verified commit | Owner | Status | Notes |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `ReportExportTest::test_pdf_render` | 2026-02-03 | `abc1234` | *(unassigned)* | open | Missing PDF binary on clean checkouts; env issue, not code |
| `LegacyImportTest::test_batch_resume` | 2026-03-18 | `def5678` | test-engineer | in progress | Ordering assumption broken by index change |

## Rules

1. **Provenance is mandatory.** Every entry records the commit at which the
   failure was last verified to pre-exist. "It was always broken" without a
   SHA is not evidence — a claimed pre-existing failure that can't be
   reproduced at its recorded commit is treated as new.
2. **QA diffs, it does not re-derive.** The ledger is the single source of
   truth for what is already broken; QA sessions must not spend cycles
   re-investigating listed entries (and must not silently expand the list —
   adding an entry requires demonstrating the failure on `{{MAIN_BRANCH}}`
   without the current change).
3. **The optional `test-engineer` agent owns burning this list down.** In the
   base team nobody owns accumulated test debt; if this ledger grows instead
   of shrinking, add the agent (see `agents/optional/test-engineer.md`).
4. **Stale entries escalate.** An entry older than **3 months** with no owner
   is an escalation to the user: either assign an owner, delete the test, or
   accept the failure explicitly in writing. Ledgers that only grow become
   noise, and noise is how real regressions slip through.
